"Bring on the secure developers It is rare for a security manager to be present from the start of a project to ensure an application is built with security controls. Security is often thought of as an add-on. Developers who specialise in security should be a key part of the project team. They should be up to date with vulnerabilities in databases, operating systems, messaging, protocols and so on. Building security into code from the beginning is starting to get more popular. Applications also need to have security/access control and compliance requirements built in. Also, third party suppliers must be monitored if they are contracted to develop an application. Backdoors may be built into the application. Other calamities such as bankruptcy or loss of key staff can leave a contractor in bits. It is vital to choose a third party provider carefully. It is rare for a client to check code built by a supplier for backdoors or security vulnerabilities. The only way around it is to conduct a thorough security review of the code. Standards exist for guidance on application security including BS7799 and Web Application Security Standards. It is not uncommon for us security professionals to experience many situations where we are introduced to a project too late. This is usually just before a system is about to go-live, where the proposal and design has already been created, and the program code has already been developed. Project teams often come to the realisation during this time; that the contract required the provider to perform security tests, undertake risk assessments, comply with the BS7799 standard or meet the needs of a piece of legislation for the solution. By the point when the system is about to “go live” the equipment has already been purchased, the code has been written, the project is probably late and there is often little money in the budget."
